	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Market and industry dynamics in the global tuna-supply chain</h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 February 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The (Forum Fisheries Agency) FFA has published a study which, over ten chapters, describes tuna supply-chain dynamics, looking at the main players in the tuna industry chain – fishing fleets, trading companies, processing and markets – focusing on the segments involved in canned tuna, sashimi, and other value-added products (such as fresh and frozen value-added products). The report also highlights the main issues facing the tuna industry, such as sustainability certification schemes, developments in the international trade regimes, EPAs, the EU’s IUU (illegal, unregulated and unreported) fishing regulation, and WTO subsidies negotiations. It also examines the implications for Pacific island countries (PICs), which comprise the majority of the members of the Western and Central Pacific Fisheries Commission (WCPFC).</p><p>On canned tuna, the study confirms that the most important canned tuna processor in the EU is Spain, with five major processing firms, four of which own their own fishing capacity. Another four EU companies are also involved in the sector, only one of which is owned by European capital. The study highlights that ‘The sale of MW Brands to Thai Union Frozen (TUF) is the most important development in the EU canned tuna industry in recent years. It has deepened relative levels of corporate concentration and centralisation of control in the global canned-tuna industry. It also means that TUF has a seat at the EU lobby group, Eurothon, which had previously focused much of its attention on the competitive threat from processors based in South-east Asia. TUF’s membership of Eurothon is likely to fragment the political coherence of the EU tuna lobby over key strategic issues such as the tuna trade regime’.</p><p>The study also revives the concept of a ‘tuna cartel’ in the Pacific: ‘PICs, as the owners of the world’s largest canning-grade tuna resources, are in a strong position to drive up the price of canned tuna, by putting in place effective limits on fishing activity and controlling supply. The market power of large retailers will continue to increase in the future, resulting in pressure on all players further down the canned-tuna supply chain. Processors, including PIC processors, will be increasingly squeezed to reduce their margins and adopt cost-cutting measures in their production plants. In order for fishing vessel operators to deflect this pressure, hard limits will need to be placed on the volume of fish caught’.</p><p>Regarding value-added products, the study underlines that global market demand for such products is relatively small in comparison to traditional canned-tuna products. However, ‘for those PIC processing facilities with export canning lines, development of value-added products does offer opportunities for increasing profitability’.</p><p>In the concluding remarks, the authors stress the very dynamic and changing nature of the tuna industry, a sector where data and analysis quickly become obsolete, as all segments of the global tuna industry are under the constant influence of multiple factors ‘including, but not limited to: tuna resource sustainability concerns, stricter regulatory requirements, increasing operating costs, technological innovation, changing consumer preferences and developments in international trade (tariff) regimes’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Study by the Forum Fisheries Agency, ‘Major Tuna Industry Status Report – “Market and Industry Dynamics in the Global Tuna Supply Chain”'<b>, </b>December 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.ffa.int/node/567  " target="_self">http://www.ffa.int/node/567</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>This study shows how important it is for PICs, but more generally for all ACP countries with tuna resources, to have a better understanding of what shapes and influences change in the global tuna-supply chain. This information is crucial for these countries to design and implement strategies and policies aimed at delivering sustainable fisheries development. However, as pointed out by the authors of this study, the sector is very dynamic and constantly changing. This suggests the need for a more permanent tool, an ‘observatory’, to enable ACP countries to stay informed of ongoing global tuna-industry developments, and develop their capacity to analyse and widely use the information produced. The development of a permanent tool of this nature may require specific support, and ACP countries should look at how the EU and other partners interested in sustainable fisheries can support such an initiative. It is worth noting that the Commission is preparing to set up a European Market Observatory for fisheries and aquaculture products whose aim is to give stakeholders, administrations and researchers a better understanding of the international and local European fisheries markets.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
